In the last decade, we have witnessed PhDs across the disciplines being awarded on the basis of publication. This process involves writing a series of papers and submitting them to an international peer-reviewed journal during the doctorate candidature. The published articles are then turned into a thesis for the award of PhD.
The minimum number of publications that may lead to the award of PhD by publication is an open question. However, the candidate must certify, among other criteria: publish a single-authored paper and at least one more paper published with the supervisor. This model of the PhD serves the following: Firstly, the job market requires researchers with prior publishing experience.





Takes away stress
A single-authored paper in international peer-reviewed journals is evidence of this experience. Secondly, co-authorship with a supervisor, is a clear demonstration of the mentorship programme and a sign of confidence amongst the scholars. Thirdly, the publications contribute immensely to institutional research performance and international ranking.
Notice that if several papers are published in peer-reviewed journals, the PhD candidate gets helpful feedback on his scholarly work before submission of the thesis. This increases chances for acceptance of the PhD thesis and hence takes away stress and anxiety from the candidate. Generally, the PhD by publications enhances the quantity and quality of scientific work.



